    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-05-08T18:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-05-08T18:10:00-05:00" n="258"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d258">
                <head>258. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant (<persName type="from"
                        >Rostow</persName>) to President <persName type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d258fn1">Source: <persName>Johnson</persName>
                        Library, National Security File, Country File, China, Vol. IX. Secret. Filed
                        with a note dictated by the President: “<persName corresp="#p_RWW1"
                            >Walt</persName>: Looks like I can’t get there from here. See if I can’t
                        find some way to bring other people into it. LBJ/mjdr. May 19, 1967. 12:30
                        p.m.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-05-08T19:10:00-04:00">May 8, 1967, 7:10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Mr. President:</p>
                <p>Herewith State’s essentially negative response to the possibility of introducing
                    more <gloss target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> personnel into South Viet Nam.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d258fn2">Attached but not printed is an April 20 memorandum
                        from <persName>Bundy</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_RD1"
                            >Rusk</persName>, with the subject heading: “Interest at Highest Levels
                        in Expanding GRC Assistance to Viet-Nam.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>On the economic side, the Vietnamese don’t really want more Chinese around,
                    although we are willing. On the military side, neither the Vietnamese nor our
                    people want Chinese forces in South Viet Nam.</p>
                <p>Behind all this is the basic negative attitude of the Vietnamese toward Chinese,
                    heightened by the large relatively wealthy Chinese population in Saigon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
